# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: css-container-queries
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] It’s been available across browsers since February 2023.
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] The **container-name** CSS property specifies a list of query container names used by the @container at-rule in a container query.
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] A case-sensitive string that is used to identify the container.
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] With no name specified, a container query will apply styles to elements based on attributes such as the size or scroll-state of the nearest ancestor with a containment context.
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] When a containment context is given a name, it can be specifically targeted by setting that name on a `@container` at-rule.
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] It is possible to create a query container by assigning a `container-name` to an element, and then query only the existence of that name in the associated `@container` at-rule, with no query expression specified.
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] These so-called **name-only container queries** enable selectively applying styles to elements based only on whether they have an ancestor with a specific `container-name` set.
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] To create a containment context, add the `container-type` property to an element in CSS.
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] Writing a container query via the `@container` at-rule will apply styles to the elements of the container when the query evaluates to true.
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] For more information on writing container queries, see the CSS Container Queries page.
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] This will allow you to target the container using either name in the `@container` at-rule.
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] This example demonstrates how to use a name-only container query.
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] We can then selectively apply styles only to elements inside containers with that name set, as shown in the next snippet.
[src:css-container-queries/container-name] The specified styles should be applied only to the first and second `<p>` elements, but not to the third.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] Container queries are an alternative to media queries, which apply styles to elements based on viewport size or other device characteristics.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] This article provides an introduction to using container queries, specifically focusing on size container queries.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] Other guides discuss style, scroll-state, and anchored container queries in detail.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] First, a media query based on the viewport's width, which is the full width of the browser.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] While container queries apply styles based on the container name or type, container size queries apply styles specifically based on the container's dimensions.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] To use container size queries, you need to declare a containment context on an element so that the browser knows you might want to query the dimensions of this container later.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] To do this, use the `container-type` property with a value of `size`, `inline-size`, or `normal`.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] The query will be based on the inline and block dimensions of the container.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] Applies layout, style, and size containment to the container.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] The query will be based on the inline dimensions of the container.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] Applies layout, style, and inline-size containment to the element.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] The element is not a query container for any container size queries, but can still be used as a query container for name-only container queries or container style queries.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] Next, use the `@container` at-rule to define a container query.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] The query in the following example will apply styles to elements based on the size of the nearest ancestor with a containment context.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] Using container queries, the card can be reused in multiple areas of a page without needing to know specifically where it will be placed each time.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] If the container with the card is narrower than `700px`, the font of the card title will be small, and if the card is in a container that's wider than `700px`, the font of the card title will be bigger.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] For more information on the syntax of container queries, see the `@container` page.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] In the previous section, a container query applied styles based on the nearest ancestor with a containment context.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] It's possible to give a containment context a name using the `container-name` property.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] Once named, the name can be used in a `@container` query so as to target a specific container.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] More information on naming containment contexts is available on the `container-name` page.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] As well as using a `container-name` along with a `<container-query>`, you can query a container using just its name.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] These so-called **name-only container queries** enable selectively applying styles to elements based on whether they have an ancestor with a specific `container-name` set.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] In this example, the specified styles would be applied only to the first and second `<p>` elements, but not to the third.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] For more information on this property, see the `container` reference.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] When applying styles to the descendants of a container using size container queries (that is, its `container-type` is set to `size` or `inline-size`), you can use container query length units.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] These units specify a length relative to the dimensions of a query container.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] Components that use units of length relative to their container are more flexible to use in different containers without having to recalculate concrete length values.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] If no eligible container is available for the query, the container query length unit defaults to the small viewport unit for that axis (`sv*`).
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] For more information on these units, see the Container query length units reference.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] For browsers that don't yet support container queries, `grid` and `flex` can be used to create a similar effect for the card component used on this page.
[src:css-container-queries/container-queries] The following example uses a `grid-template-columns` declaration to create a two-column layout for the card component.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] The **container-type** CSS property specifies the type of container context used in a container query.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] The `container-type` property can take a single value from the list below, or two values.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] In the two-value case, one must be `scroll-state` and the other can be `inline-size` or `size`.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] Establishes a query container for anchored container queries on the container.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] In this case, the size of the element is not computed in isolation; no containment is applied.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] Establishes a query container for dimensional queries on the inline axis of the container.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] Applies style and inline-size containment to the element.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] The inline size of the element can be computed in isolation, ignoring the child elements (see Using CSS containment).
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] The element is not a query container for any container size, scroll-state, or anchored queries, but can be used as a query container for container style queries and name-only container queries.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] Establishes a query container for scroll-state queries on the container.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] Establishes a query container for container size queries in both the inline and block dimensions.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] Applies style and size containment to the element.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] Size containment is applied to the element in both the inline and block directions.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] The size of the element can be computed in isolation, ignoring the child elements.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] Container queries allow you to selectively apply styles inside a container based on conditional queries performed on the container.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] The `@container` at-rule is used to specify the tests performed on a container, and the rules that will apply to the container's contents if the query returns `true`.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] If a `container-type` is not set on a container, the element is not a query container for container size, scroll-state, or anchored queries, but can still be used as a query container for container style queries and name-only container queries.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] Container size queries allow you to selectively apply CSS rules to a container's descendants based on a size condition such as a maximum or minimum dimension, aspect ratio, or orientation.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] Size containers additionally have size containment applied to them — this turns off the ability of an element to get size information from its contents, which is important for container queries to avoid infinite loops.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] If this were not the case, a CSS rule inside a container query could change the content size, which in turn could make the query evaluate to false and change the parent element's size, which in turn could change the content size and flip the query back to true, and so on.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] This sequence would then repeat itself in an endless loop.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] The container size has to be set by context, such as block-level elements that stretch to the full width of their parent, or explicitly defined.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] If a contextual or explicit size is not available, elements with size containment will collapse.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] In the first case, the queried container is the scroll container itself.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] In the other two cases the queried container is an element that is affected by the scroll position of an ancestor scroll container.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] Anchored container queries allow you to selectively apply CSS rules to the descendants of an anchor-positioned container when it has a position-try fallback active on it, as specified via the `position-try-fallbacks` property.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] For example, you might have an anchor-positioned tooltip element that is positioned above its anchor by default via a `position-area` value of `top`, but has a `position-try-fallbacks` value of `flip-block` specified.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] This will cause the tooltip to flip in the block direction to the bottom of its anchor when it starts to overflow the top of the viewport.
[src:css-container-queries/container-type] If we set `container-type: anchored` on it, we can detect when the position-try fallback is applied via a `@container` at-rule and apply CSS as a result.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] It’s been available across browsers since March 2022.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] The **`contain`** CSS property indicates that an element and its contents are, as much as possible, independent from the rest of the document tree.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] Containment enables isolating a subsection of the DOM, providing performance benefits by limiting calculations of layout, style, paint, size, or any combination to a DOM subtree rather than the entire page.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] Containment can also be used to scope CSS counters and quotes.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] The element renders as normal, with no containment applied.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] All containment rules are applied to the element.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] This is equivalent to `contain: size layout paint style`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] All containment rules except `size` are applied to the element.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] This is equivalent to `contain: layout paint style`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] This value cannot be combined with `inline-size`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] Inline size containment is applied to the element.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] The inline size of the element can be computed in isolation, ignoring the child elements.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] This value cannot be combined with `size`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] The internal layout of the element is isolated from the rest of the page.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] This means nothing outside the element affects its internal layout, and vice versa.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] For properties that can affect more than just an element and its descendants, the effects don't escape the containing element.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] Counters and quotes are scoped to the element and its contents.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] Descendants of the element don't display outside its bounds.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] If the containing box is offscreen, the browser does not need to paint its contained elements — these must also be offscreen as they are contained completely by that box.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] If a descendant overflows the containing element's bounds, then that descendant will be clipped to the containing element's border-box.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] There are four types of CSS containment: size, layout, style, and paint, which are set on the container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] The property is a space-separated list of a subset of the five standard values or one of the two shorthand values.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] Changes to the contained properties within the container are not propagated outside of the contained element to the rest of the page.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] The main benefit of containment is that the browser does not have to re-render the DOM or page layout as often, leading to small performance benefits during the rendering of static pages and greater performance benefits in more dynamic applications.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] Using the `contain` property is useful on pages with groups of elements that are supposed to be independent, as it can prevent element internals from having side effects outside of its bounding-box.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] The following example shows how to use `contain: paint` to prevent an element's descendants from painting outside of its bounds.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] The first card has layout containment applied, and its layout is isolated from the rest of the page.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] We can reuse this card in other places on the page without worrying about layout recalculation of the other elements.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] If floats overlap the card bounds, elements on the rest of the page are not affected.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] When the browser recalculates the containing element's subtree, only that element is recalculated.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] Nothing outside of the contained element needs to be recalculated.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] Additionally, the fixed box uses the card as a layout container to position itself.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] The second and third cards have no containment.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] The layout context for the fixed box in the second card is the root element so the fixed box is positioned in the top right corner of the page.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] A float overlaps the second card's bounds causing the third card to have unexpected layout shift that's visible in the positioning of the `<h2>` element.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] When recalculation occurs, it is not limited to a container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] This impacts performance and interferes with the rest of the page layout.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] Style containment scopes counters and quotes to the contained element.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] For CSS counters, the `counter-increment` and `counter-set` properties are scoped to the element as if the element is at the root of the document.
[src:css-container-queries/css-contain] Without containment, the counter would increment from 1 to 5 for each list item.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The **`@container`** CSS at-rule is a conditional group rule that applies styles to a containment context.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Style declarations are filtered by a condition and applied to the elements within the container if the condition is true.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The condition is evaluated when the queried container size, `<style-feature>`, or scroll-state changes.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The condition must specify a `container-name`, and `<container-query>`, or both.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The `container-name` property specifies a list of query container names, which are used to filter which containers are targeted by the `@container` rules.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] If only a `container-name` value is included (a name-only container query), the contained rules are applied to any containers with one or more of those `container-name` values set on them.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container features in the `<container-query>` are evaluated against the selected containers.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] If no `<container-name>` is specified, the `<container-query>` features are evaluated against the nearest ancestor query container that has the matching `container-type`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] One or both of `<container-name>` and `<container-query>`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Styles defined in the `<stylesheet>` are applied if the condition is `true`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The name of the container to query; it is specified as an `<ident>`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] If the query evaluates to `true`, the declared styles are applied to the container's descendant elements.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] A set of features that are evaluated against the query container when the size, `<style-feature>`, scroll-state, or applied position-try fallback of the container changes.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] A containment context can be named using the `container-name` property.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Details about usage and naming restrictions are described in the `container-name` page.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The `<container-condition>` queries include size, scroll-state, and anchored container descriptors.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The `<container-condition>` can include one or more boolean size queries, each within a set of parentheses.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] A size query includes a size descriptor, a value, and — depending on the descriptor — a comparison operator.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The queries always measure the content box as the comparison.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The syntax for including multiple conditions is the same as for `@media` size feature queries.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The `aspect-ratio` of the container calculated as the width to the height of the container expressed as a `<ratio>` value.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The `block-size` of the container expressed as a `<length>` value.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The height of the container expressed as a `<length>` value.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The `inline-size` of the container expressed as a `<length>` value.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The orientation of the container, either `landscape` or `portrait`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The width of the container expressed as a `<length>` value.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Supported keywords for scroll-state container descriptors include physical and flow relative values.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Queries whether the container can be scrolled in the given direction via user-initiated scrolling, such as by dragging the scrollbar or using a trackpad gesture.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] In other words, is there overflowing content in the given direction that can be scrolled to?
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is not a scroll container or otherwise cannot be scrolled in any direction.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container can be scrolled towards its top edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container can be scrolled towards its right-hand edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container can be scrolled towards its bottom edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container can be scrolled towards its left-hand edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container can be scrolled horizontally towards either or both of its left-hand or right-hand edges.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container can be scrolled vertically towards either or both of its top or bottom edges.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container can be scrolled towards its block-start edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container can be scrolled towards its block-end edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container can be scrolled towards its inline-start edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container can be scrolled towards its inline-end edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container can be scrolled in its block direction towards either or both of its block-start or block-end edges.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container can be scrolled in its inline direction towards either or both of its inline-start and inline-end edges.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] If the test passes, the rules inside the `@container` block are applied to descendants of the scroll container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Queries whether the container was most recently scrolled in a specified direction.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is not a scroll container or otherwise has not previously been scrolled in any direction.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container was most recently scrolled towards its top edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container was most recently scrolled towards its right-hand edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container was most recently scrolled towards its bottom edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container was most recently scrolled towards its left-hand edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container was most recently scrolled towards either its left-hand or right-hand edges.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container was most recently scrolled towards either its top or bottom edges.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container was most recently scrolled towards its block-start edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container was most recently scrolled towards its block-end edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container was most recently scrolled towards its inline-start edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container was most recently scrolled towards its inline-end edge.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container was most recently scrolled towards either its block-start or block-end edges.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container was most recently scrolled towards either its inline-start or inline-end edges.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] If the test returns true, the rules nested in the `@container` block are applied to the descendants of the scroll container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Queries whether the container is going to be snapped to a scroll snap container ancestor along the given axis.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is not a scroll snap target for its ancestor scroll container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] When implementing a `snapped: none` query, containers that *are* snap targets for the scroll container will *not* have the `@container` styles applied, whereas non-snap targets *will* have the styles applied.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is a horizontal scroll snap target for its ancestor scroll container, that is, it is snapping horizontally to its ancestor.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is a vertical scroll snap target for its ancestor scroll container, that is, it is snapping vertically to its ancestor.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is a block-axis scroll snap target for its ancestor scroll container, that is, it is snapping to its ancestor in the block direction.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is an inline-axis scroll snap target for its ancestor scroll container, that is, it is snapping to its ancestor in the inline direction.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is both a horizontal and vertical scroll snap target for its ancestor scroll container and is snapping to its ancestor in both directions.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container won't match if it is only snapping to its ancestor along the horizontal *or* vertical axis.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] To evaluate a container with a non-`none` `snapped` scroll-state query, it must be a container with a scroll container ancestor having a `scroll-snap-type` value other than `none`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] A `snapped: none` query will match even when there is no scroll container ancestor.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Evaluations occur when `scrollsnapchanging` events fire on the scroll snap container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] If the test passes, the rules inside the `@container` block are applied to descendants of the container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Queries whether a container with a `position` value of `sticky` is stuck to an edge of its scrolling container ancestor.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is not stuck to any edges of its container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Note that `none` queries will match even if the container does not have `position: sticky` set on it.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is stuck to the top edge of its container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is stuck to the right-hand edge of its container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is stuck to the bottom edge of its container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is stuck to the left-hand edge of its container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is stuck to the block-start edge of its container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is stuck to the block-end edge of its container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is stuck to the inline-start edge of its container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The container is stuck to the inline-end edge of its container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] To evaluate a container with a non-`none` `stuck` scroll-state query, it must have `position: sticky` set on it, and be inside a scroll container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] If the test passes, the rules inside the `@container` block are applied to descendants of the `position: sticky` container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Queries whether a specific position-try fallback is currently active on an anchor-positioned container, as specified via the `position-try-fallbacks` property.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Valid `fallback` values include any component value that is valid for inclusion in a `position-try-fallbacks` property value.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] If the `fallback` value named in the test is currently active on the anchor-positioned container, the test passes, and the rules inside the `@container` block are applied to descendants of the anchor-positioned container.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] A container context can be created using the `container-type` property, in this case using the `inline-size` value on the `.post` class.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] You can then use the `@container` at-rule to apply styles to the element with the `.card` class in a container that's narrower than `650px`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] First, create a container context using the `container-type` and `container-name` properties.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The shorthand syntax for this declaration is described in the `container` page.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] It's not possible to target multiple containers in a single container query.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] It is possible to nest container queries which has the same effect.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Container queries can also evaluate the computed style of the container element.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] A *container style query* is a `@container` query that uses one or more `style()` functional notations.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The boolean syntax and logic combining style features into a style query is the same as for CSS feature queries.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The parameter of each `style()` is a single `<style-feature>`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] A **`<style-feature>`** can be a valid CSS declaration (the **plain** form), a CSS property or `<custom-property-name>` on its own (the **boolean** form), or a range comparison (the **range** form).
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] A style feature without a value evaluates to true if the computed value is different from the initial value for the given property.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] If the `<style-feature>` passed as the `style()` function's argument is a declaration, the style query evaluates to true if the declaration's value is the same as the computed value of that property for the container being queried.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Style features that query a shorthand property are true if the computed values match for each of its longhand properties, and false otherwise.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] For example, `@container style(border: 2px solid red)` will resolve to true if all 12 longhand properties (`border-bottom-style`, etc.) that make up that shorthand are true.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Note that `!important` is allowed in style queries but is ignored.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The global `revert` and `revert-layer` are invalid as values in a `<style-feature>` and cause the container style query to be false.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] In addition to the plain `<style-feature-name>: <value>` form described above, a `<style-feature>` can be written as a **range** comparison using `=`, `<`, `<=`, `>`, or `>=`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Range syntax enables **numeric** comparisons that the plain form can't, such as `style(--columns >= 3)` or `style(--gap = 1rem)`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] It compares the resolved values of both sides numerically.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] If either side can't be parsed as one of those types, or the two sides don't have the same type, the query is false.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Computes each side (evaluating any `calc()` expressions) and performs the numeric comparison.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] This means range syntax can't be used to compare keyword-like values: `style(--theme = dark)` is always false because `dark` isn't a numeric type.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] Use the plain syntax for those, for example `style(--theme: dark)`.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] The middle value is tested against both bounds, rather than being chained left-to-right.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] See Using container scroll-state queries for scroll-state query examples.
[src:css-container-queries/css-container] See Using anchored container queries for anchored query examples.
